{{afc comment|1=This is questionable as I think it requires [[WP:MEDRS]] and I am surprised that jawiki has these claims not only not medically sourced but without medically reliable sources[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 00:10, 14 March 2025 (UTC)}} [[File:Tamagoyu, 天渓の湯 01.jpg|thumb|right|An example of a sulfur spring: the "Tenkei no Yu" at {{ill|Takayu Onsen|ja|高湯温泉|12=draft}} ]] '''Sulfur Spring''' (硫黄泉, Iōsen) is a classification of {{ill|onsen|ja|温泉|1=Onsen|12=draft}}<nowiki/>based on the {{ill|Hot Spring Types|ja|温泉の泉質|12=draft}} labeling system. It is categorized as a {{ill|medical spring|ja|温泉#療養泉|12=draft}} due to its unique components. == Overview == Sulfur springs are characterized by a rotten egg smell caused by {{ill|hydrogen sulfide|en|Hydrogen sulfide|12=draft}}<nowiki/>and the frequent occurrence of cloudy water due to {{ill|Yunohana|ja|湯の花|1=Yunohana|12=draft}} (mineral deposits). While the labeling system categorizes all sulfur springs under a single term, they are generally divided into two main types based on the presence or absence of hydrogen sulfide: sulfur-based springs and '''hydrogen sulfide springs.''' Identification of the type can be made using the new or old water quality labels.
The pH range of sulfur springs varies widely. Springs with higher acidity (lower pH) are typically hydrogen sulfide springs, while those with higher alkalinity are often sulfur-based. Notable high-sulfur concentration onsen in Japan include {{ill|Takayu Onsen|ja|高湯温泉|12=draft}}(Fukushima), {{ill|Manza Onsen|ja|万座温泉|12=draft}} (Gunma), and {{ill|Tsukioka Onsen|ja|月岡温泉|12=draft}} (Niigata). == Definition == Sulfur springs are defined as containing at least 2 mg of total sulfur (S) per kilogram of water, including HS-, S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>--, and H<sub>2</sub>S.<ref>[https://www.env.go.jp/nature/onsen/point/ Definition and Protection of Onsen - Ministry of the Environment]</ref>
== Comparison of Old and New Labels == {| class="wikitable" |+ Comparison of Old and New Onsen Water Quality Labels<ref>{{Cite web|title=Reference Material: Comparison of Old and New Onsen Water Quality Labels |url=https://www.env.go.jp/nature/onsen/docs/senshitsumei26.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=Natural Environment Bureau, Ministry of the Environment |accessdate=2018-03-26 }} </ref> ! Old Label !! New Label !! Abbreviated Label |- | Sulfur Spring || Sulfur Spring || S Spring |- | Simple Sulfur Spring || Simple Sulfur Spring || Simple S Spring |- | Sulfur and Sodium Chloride Spring || Sulfur and Sodium Chloride Spring || S-Na-Cl Spring |- | Sulfur and Sodium Bicarbonate-Chloride Spring || Sulfur and Sodium Bicarbonate-Chloride Spring || S-Na-Cl･HCO<sub>3</sub> Spring |- | Hydrogen Sulfide Spring || Sulfur Spring (Hydrogen Sulfide Type) || S Spring (H<sub>2</sub>S Type) |}
== Health Benefits == ''Note: [[Health effects of hot springs|Effects]] are not guaranteed for all individuals.''
Benefits associated with sulfur springs include the following:
=== Indications === ==== Bathing ==== * '''General indications:''' Chronic {{ill|skin diseases|en|Skin disease|12=draft}}, chronic {{ill|gynecological disorders|en|Gynecological disorder|12=draft}} , {{ill|cuts|en|Cut (wound)|12=draft}} , and {{ill|diabetes|en|Diabetes mellitus|12=draft}} .
* '''Hydrogen sulfide type:''' Effective for {{ill|hypertension|en|Hypertension|12=draft}}<nowiki/>and {{ill|arteriosclerosis|en|Arteriosclerosis|12=draft}} .
==== Drinking ==== * Beneficial for diabetes, {{ill|gout|en|Gout|12=draft}}, {{ill|constipation|en|Constipation|12=draft}} , and {{ill|diarrhea|en|Diarrhea|12=draft}} . === Contraindications === ==== Bathing ==== * '''General contraindications:''' Overly sensitive {{ill|skin|en|Human skin|12=draft}}<nowiki/>or {{ill|mucous membranes|en|Mucous membrane|12=draft}}, particularly in individuals with {{ill|photosensitivity|en|Photosensitivity|12=draft}} .<ref>[https://www.env.go.jp/nature/onsen/pdf/pamph_full_en.pdf Onsen_ABC]</ref> == Representative Onsen == * {{ill|Kawayu Onsen (Hokkaido)|ja|川湯温泉 (北海道)|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Hakone Yumoto Onsen|ja|箱根湯本温泉|12=draft}}(Kanagawa Prefecture)
* {{ill|Nikkō Yumoto Onsen|ja|日光湯元温泉|12=draft}}(Tochigi Prefecture)
* {{ill|Kusatsu Onsen|ja|草津温泉|12=draft}}(Gunma Prefecture)
* {{ill|Manza Onsen|ja|万座温泉|12=draft}}(Gunma Prefecture)
* {{ill|Nozawa Onsen|ja|野沢温泉|12=draft}}(Nagano Prefecture)
* Ebino Kōgen Onsen (Miyazaki Prefecture)
== Accidents == Hydrogen sulfide springs can release hydrogen sulfide gas into the air, which may cause {{ill|poisoning|en|Poisoning|12=draft}}<nowiki/>when inhaled in large concentrations or for extended periods. Proper {{ill|ventilation|en|Ventilation (architecture)|12=draft}} is essential in indoor baths. In outdoor springs or {{ill|wilderness hot springs|ja|野湯|1=Wilderness hot springs|12=draft}}, high-concentration hydrogen sulfide gas, which is heavier than air, tends to accumulate in depressions or hollows, potentially leading to fatal poisoning incidents.<ref group="注">Between 1935 and 1985, nine deaths occurred at {{ill|Jigokudani Onsen (Tateyama)|ja|地獄谷 (立山町)|12=draft}} .</ref> Snow-covered onsen in winter can also trap gas, increasing the risk of poisoning.<ref>[http://www.iamp.tohoku.ac.jp/~liquid/MURA/hitorigoto/gas-kiji/h2s.html Hydrogen Sulfide Poisoning Incidents]</ref> {{Seealso|Hydrogen sulfide#Toxicity}}
