== Health Benefits == ''Note: [[Health effects of hot springs|Effects]] are not guaranteed for all individuals.''
Benefits associated with sulfur springs include the following:
=== Indications === ==== Bathing ==== * '''General indications:''' Chronic {{ill|skin diseases|en|Skin disease|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, chronic {{ill|gynecological disorders|en|Gynecological disorder|qq=draft|qq=draft}} , {{ill|cuts|en|Cut (wound)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} , and {{ill|diabetes|en|Diabetes mellitus|qq=draft|qq=draft}} .
* '''Hydrogen sulfide type:''' Effective for {{ill|hypertension|en|Hypertension|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<nowiki/>and {{ill|arteriosclerosis|en|Arteriosclerosis|qq=draft|qq=draft}} .
==== Drinking ==== * Beneficial for diabetes, {{ill|gout|en|Gout|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|constipation|en|Constipation|qq=draft|qq=draft}} , and {{ill|diarrhea|en|Diarrhea|qq=draft|qq=draft}} . === Contraindications === ==== Bathing ==== * '''General contraindications:''' Overly sensitive {{ill|skin|en|Human skin|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<nowiki/>or {{ill|mucous membranes|en|Mucous membrane|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, particularly in individuals with {{ill|photosensitivity|en|Photosensitivity|qq=draft|qq=draft}} .<ref>[https://www.env.go.jp/nature/onsen/pdf/pamph_full_en.pdf Onsen_ABC]</ref> == Representative Onsen == * {{ill|Kawayu Onsen (Hokkaido)|ja|川湯温泉 (北海道)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Hakone Yumoto Onsen|ja|箱根湯本温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}(Kanagawa Prefecture)
* {{ill|Nikkō Yumoto Onsen|ja|日光湯元温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}(Tochigi Prefecture)
* {{ill|Kusatsu Onsen|ja|草津温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}(Gunma Prefecture)
* {{ill|Manza Onsen|ja|万座温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}(Gunma Prefecture)
* {{ill|Nozawa Onsen|ja|野沢温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}(Nagano Prefecture)
* Ebino Kōgen Onsen (Miyazaki Prefecture)
== Accidents == Hydrogen sulfide springs can release hydrogen sulfide gas into the air, which may cause {{ill|poisoning|en|Poisoning|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<nowiki/>when inhaled in large concentrations or for extended periods. Proper {{ill|ventilation|en|Ventilation (architecture)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} is essential in indoor baths. In outdoor springs or {{ill|wilderness hot springs|ja|野湯|1=Wilderness hot springs|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, high-concentration hydrogen sulfide gas, which is heavier than air, tends to accumulate in depressions or hollows, potentially leading to fatal poisoning incidents.<ref group="注">Between 1935 and 1985, nine deaths occurred at {{ill|Jigokudani Onsen (Tateyama)|ja|地獄谷 (立山町)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} .</ref> Snow-covered onsen in winter can also trap gas, increasing the risk of poisoning.<ref>[http://www.iamp.tohoku.ac.jp/~liquid/MURA/hitorigoto/gas-kiji/h2s.html Hydrogen Sulfide Poisoning Incidents]</ref> {{Seealso|Hydrogen sulfide#Toxicity}}
