'''Sulfur Spring''' (硫黄泉, Iōsen) is a classification of {{ill|onsen|ja|温泉|1=Onsen|1=Onsen|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<nowiki/>based on the {{ill|Hot Spring Types|ja|温泉の泉質|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
labeling system. It is categorized as a {{ill|medical spring|ja|温泉#療養泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
due to its unique components.
== Overview ==
Sulfur springs are characterized by a rotten egg smell caused by {{ill|hydrogen sulfide|en|Hydrogen sulfide|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<nowiki/>and the frequent occurrence of cloudy water due to {{ill|Yunohana|ja|湯の花|1=Yunohana|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
(mineral deposits). While the labeling system categorizes all sulfur springs under a single term, they are generally divided into two main types based on the presence or absence of hydrogen sulfide: sulfur-based springs and '''hydrogen sulfide springs.''' Identification of the type can be made using the new or old water quality labels.

The pH range of sulfur springs varies widely. Springs with higher acidity (lower pH) are typically hydrogen sulfide springs, while those with higher alkalinity are often sulfur-based. Notable high-sulfur concentration onsen in Japan include {{ill|Takayu Onsen|ja|高湯温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}(Fukushima), {{ill|Manza Onsen|ja|万座温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
(Gunma), and {{ill|Tsukioka Onsen|ja|月岡温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
(Niigata).
== Definition ==
Sulfur springs are defined as containing at least 2 mg of total sulfur (S) per kilogram of water, including HS-, S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>--, and H<sub>2</sub>S.<ref>[https://www.env.go.jp/nature/onsen/point/ Definition and Protection of Onsen - Ministry of the Environment]</ref>

