* {{ill|Nozawa Onsen|ja|野沢温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft}}(Nagano Prefecture)

* Ebino Kōgen Onsen (Miyazaki Prefecture)

== Accidents ==
Hydrogen sulfide springs can release hydrogen sulfide gas into the air, which may cause {{ill|poisoning|en|Poisoning|qq=draft|qq=draft}}<nowiki/>when inhaled in large concentrations or for extended periods. Proper {{ill|ventilation|en|Ventilation (architecture)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
is essential in indoor baths. In outdoor springs or {{ill|wilderness hot springs|ja|野湯|1=Wilderness hot springs|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, high-concentration hydrogen sulfide gas, which is heavier than air, tends to accumulate in depressions or hollows, potentially leading to fatal poisoning incidents.<ref group="注">Between 1935 and 1985, nine deaths occurred at {{ill|Jigokudani Onsen (Tateyama)|ja|地獄谷 (立山町)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
.</ref> Snow-covered onsen in winter can also trap gas, increasing the risk of poisoning.<ref>[http://www.iamp.tohoku.ac.jp/~liquid/MURA/hitorigoto/gas-kiji/h2s.html Hydrogen Sulfide Poisoning Incidents]</ref>
