{{afc comment|1=This is questionable as I think it requires [[WP:MEDRS]] and I am surprised that jawiki has these claims not only not medically sourced but without medically reliable sources[[User:Immanuelle|Immanuelle]] ([[User talk:Immanuelle|talk]]) 00:10, 14 March 2025 (UTC)}}
[[File:Tamagoyu, 天渓の湯 01.jpg|thumb|right|An example of a sulfur spring: the "Tenkei no Yu" at {{ill|Takayu Onsen|ja|高湯温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takayu Onsen|qq=}} ]] '''Sulfur Spring''' (硫黄泉, Iōsen) is a classification of {{ill|onsen|ja|温泉|1=Onsen|1=Onsen|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/onsen|13=User:Immanuelle/Onsen|qq=}}<nowiki/>based on the {{ill|Hot Spring Types|ja|温泉の泉質|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hot Spring Types|qq=}} labeling system. It is categorized as a {{ill|medical spring|ja|温泉#療養泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/medical spring|qq=}} due to its unique components. == Overview == Sulfur springs are characterized by a rotten egg smell caused by {{ill|hydrogen sulfide|en|Hydrogen sulfide|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/hydrogen sulfide|qq=}}<nowiki/>and the frequent occurrence of cloudy water due to {{ill|Yunohana|ja|湯の花|1=Yunohana|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yunohana|13=User:Immanuelle/Yunohana|qq=}} (mineral deposits). While the labeling system categorizes all sulfur springs under a single term, they are generally divided into two main types based on the presence or absence of hydrogen sulfide: sulfur-based springs and '''hydrogen sulfide springs.''' Identification of the type can be made using the new or old water quality labels.
The pH range of sulfur springs varies widely. Springs with higher acidity (lower pH) are typically hydrogen sulfide springs, while those with higher alkalinity are often sulfur-based. Notable high-sulfur concentration onsen in Japan include {{ill|Takayu Onsen|ja|高湯温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takayu Onsen|qq=}}(Fukushima), {{ill|Manza Onsen|ja|万座温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Manza Onsen|qq=}} (Gunma), and {{ill|Tsukioka Onsen|ja|月岡温泉|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsukioka Onsen|qq=}} (Niigata). == Definition == Sulfur springs are defined as containing at least 2 mg of total sulfur (S) per kilogram of water, including HS-, S<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>--, and H<sub>2</sub>S.<ref>[https://www.env.go.jp/nature/onsen/point/ Definition and Protection of Onsen - Ministry of the Environment]</ref>
== Comparison of Old and New Labels == {| class="wikitable" |+ Comparison of Old and New Onsen Water Quality Labels<ref>{{Cite web|title=Reference Material: Comparison of Old and New Onsen Water Quality Labels |url=https://www.env.go.jp/nature/onsen/docs/senshitsumei26.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=Natural Environment Bureau, Ministry of the Environment |accessdate=2018-03-26 }} </ref> ! Old Label !! New Label !! Abbreviated Label |- | Sulfur Spring || Sulfur Spring || S Spring |- | Simple Sulfur Spring || Simple Sulfur Spring || Simple S Spring |- | Sulfur and Sodium Chloride Spring || Sulfur and Sodium Chloride Spring || S-Na-Cl Spring |- | Sulfur and Sodium Bicarbonate-Chloride Spring || Sulfur and Sodium Bicarbonate-Chloride Spring || S-Na-Cl･HCO<sub>3</sub> Spring |- | Hydrogen Sulfide Spring || Sulfur Spring (Hydrogen Sulfide Type) || S Spring (H<sub>2</sub>S Type) |}
